Here is a robust, multi-engine audit for a complex Drupal component (e.g., an accessible modal dialog).

### 1. Twig Template (`modal.html.twig`)
```twig
<div class="modal" role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="modal-title" aria-describedby="modal-desc">
  <h2 id="modal-title" class="visually-hidden">{{ title }}</h2>
  <p id="modal-desc">{{ description }}</p>
  <button class="modal-close" aria-label="Close dialog">&times;</button>
  <div class="modal-body">{{ content }}</div>
</div>
```

### 2. Drush Command (Post-deploy validation hook)
```php
// In drush.services.yml:
// services:
//   drush.command.modal_validation:
//     class: \Drupal\modal_tools\Commands\ModalValidationCommands

/**
 * @command modal:validate-accessibility
 */
public function validate(): void {
  $this->logger()->info('Validating modal accessibility…');
  $result = drush_shell_output('playwright test tests/modal.spec.ts');
  $this->logger()->success($result ? 'All modal tests passed.' : 'Modal accessibility issues detected.');
}
```

### 3. Playwright Test (axe-core + Alfa)
```ts
// tests/modal.spec.ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';
import AxeBuilder from '@axe-core/playwright';
import { Alfa } from '@siteimprove/alfa-playwright';

test('Modal dialog meets SC 4.1.2, SC 1.3.1, SC 2.4.7', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.setContent(`
    <div class="modal" role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="modal-title" aria-describedby="modal-desc">
      <h2 id="modal-title">Confirm Action</h2>
      <p id="modal-desc">Are you sure?</p>
      <button aria-label="Close dialog">×</button>
    </div>
  `);

  // Axe-core: SC 4.1.2 requires role, name, and value
  const axe = await new AxeBuilder({ page })
    .withTags(['wcag2a', 'wcag2aa'])
    .include('[role="dialog"]')
    .analyze();

  const violations = axe.violations.filter(v =>
    v.id === 'aria-required-attr' ||
    v.id === 'aria-allowed-attr' ||
    v.id === 'aria-valid-attr-value'
  );

  expect(violations).toHaveLength(0);

  // Alfa: Full tree validation
  const alfa = await Alfa.fromPage(page).run();
  const dialog = alfa.filter(r => r.target.toString().includes('role="dialog"'));

  // Expect: role = dialog, aria-modal = true, aria-labelledby points to existing ID
  expect(dialog.every(r => r.outcome === 'Passed')).toBe(true);

  // Manual SC 4.1.2 checks
  const modal = page.locator('[role="dialog"]');
  await expect(modal).toHaveAttribute('aria-modal', 'true');
  await expect(modal).toHaveAccessibleName('Confirm Action');
  await expect(page.locator('[aria-label="Close dialog"]')).toBeVisible();
});
```

### Why `toHaveAccessibleName()` is insufficient:
- It does *not* verify `role`, `aria-required-attributes`, or `aria-allowed-attributes`.
- SC 4.1.2 violations often appear as missing `aria-*` attributes (e.g., `aria-modal` on dialog).
- Dual-engine audit catches both semantic errors (Alfa) and implementation errors (axe).

### Checklist for full SC 4.1.2 compliance:
✅ `role` explicitly set (e.g., `dialog`, `button`, `navigation`)  
✅ `aria-*` attributes used per spec (no invalid ones, required ones present)  
✅ `id`s referenced by `aria-labelledby`/`aria-describedby` exist  
✅ Values are non-empty and valid (e.g., `aria-hidden="true"`, not `aria-hidden="yes"`)

Use `drush modal:validate-accessibility` in CI to enforce.

